Verbindung von Schöpfung als Kommunikationsgeschehen mit einer ihre "grammatischen" Strukturen erschließenden Naturerkenntnis.  aThis systematic theological study uses the example of Johann Georg Hamann (1730-1788) to examine and systematically develop the question of determining the relationship of theology and natural science. In the course of translating basic structures of an "objective" view of the world into categories of a linguistic-hermeneutic understanding of reality, Hamann makes possible a connection of creation as a communicative process with an understanding of nature which opens up its "grammatical" structures.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCreationxHistory of doctrinesy18th century. 0aHermeneuticsxHistoryy18th century. 0aNatural theologyxHistoryy18th century. 0aNaturexReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory of doctrinesy18th century. 0aReligion and sciencexHistoryy18th century. 4aHamann, Johann Georg. 4aNaturwissenschaft. 4aSchöpfung. 4aSystematische Theologie. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / Systematic.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Theology and Religious Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110638165oZDB-23-GTR0 cprintz978311017018440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311090060640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110900606423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110900606/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-GTRc2000d2014